Frequently Asked Questions
Do you have a question for us? You may find your answer here. And if you don't, please Contact Us.


Search for:





CEA Information


  
Why CEA earthquake insurance? 

CEA has reduced homeowners rates since 1996 by nearly 55 percent, making earthquake insurance more affordable than ever!
As a not-for-profit, CEA rates are based on science and straightforward, objective risk factors. Determining factors are the insured value, location, construction- and foundation-types, age, number of stories and coverage choices.
 







  
Is CEA a state agency? 

No. CEA is a public instrumentality of the state. An instrumentality is an organization created by state law and operated for public purposes. Learn more about CEA’s creation after the Northridge earthquake and history.

CEA is financed solely through insurer contributions, policyholder premiums, and its own investment returns. We are a not-for-profit and receive no funding from the State of California, whether for operations or claim liabilities, and are not a part of the state budget. 
  






  
Who handles CEA applications, renewals and claims? 

Participating insurance companies and their agents process all policy applications, renewals, payments and claims. 
  






  
Who do I contact if I have questions or an earthquake damage claim? 

Participating insurance companies process all policy applications, renewals, payments and claims. CEA policyholders should contact your insurance company’s customer service or claim department regarding policy renewals, changes to an existing policy or the handling of claims. Customers make payment of CEA premiums to your insurance company, not to the CEA. 
  






  
Why doesn't CEA accept credit card payments or ACH withdrawals? 

Each CEA participating insurance company handles billing for their CEA customers, including establishing the number of installment payments and methods of payment. Customers can pay their bills using whatever payment method their participating insurance company offers. 
  






  
If I have to move out of my property due to damages caused by an earthquake, how does CEA handle this? 


If you purchased Loss of Use coverage, you are eligible for the additional living expenses necessary to maintain your normal standard of living, up to the coverage limit you selected.
If selected, Loss of Use coverage is offered in limits of $1,500, $10,000, $15,000, $25,000, $50,000, $75,000 and $100,000.
If you have a CEA Renters policy, rest easy. CEA will pay for your additional living expense, according to the policy terms, limits, and conditions, if you need to move out while your landlord makes repairs, or while you look for a new residence to move into. 
If you are a landlord and you have a CEA policy on the rental property, CEA will pay, in accordance with policy terms, limits, and conditions, the fair rental value for your rental property under the Loss of Use coverage. 








  
Can loss of use be used even if the damages do not exceed the deductible?  

Yes. Two CEA coverages come with zero deductible: the first $1,500 of emergency repairs for homeowners and mobilehome owners, and, if a home can't be occupied after an earthquake, additional living expenses up to the Loss of Use coverage you selected.  
  






  
Does CEA offer coverage for items like crystal, china and porcelain? 

You can add "breakables" coverage as an option on your policy (subject to sublimit), to cover breakable belongings such as dishes and ceramics.





CEA Financial Strength


  
Will CEA be able to pay all of its claims if there is an earthquake? 

CEA has a claim-paying capacity of more than $15 billion. Also:

CEA is financially sound, with an A- (Excellent) rating from A.M. Best Co., the world's leading rating agency of insurance companies.
CEA is privately funded. We don't receive any money from the state, so state budgets or budget deficits have no impact on our ability to pay claims.
CEA could cover all its claims if the 1906 San Francisco, 1989 Loma Prieta, or 1994 Northridge earthquake reoccurred today.
	 








  
How much claim-paying capacity does CEA have? 

CEA has more than $15 billion in claims paying capacity and has maintained an A- (Excellent) rating with A.M Best. CEA could cover all its claims if the 1906 San Francisco, 1989 Loma Prieta, or 1994 Northridge earthquake reoccurred today.

Read more about CEA's financial strength. 
  




Homeowners and Mobilehome Owners


  
How much does a CEA homeowners earthquake insurance policy cost? 

The minimum annual premium for a CEA standard Homeowners or Homeowners Choice policy is $100. Various rating factors determine your premium, such as:

Degree of earthquake risk where you live
Insured value of the house
The house's number of stories, age, and foundation and construction type
The policy coverages, limits and deductibles you choose
Whether or not the insured dwelling has been seismically retrofitted, per defined building code standards, and qualifies for the Hazard Reduction Discount

Find a homeowners policy that works with your budget and coverage needs. And use our Premium Calculator to get a policy premium estimate.







  
How much does a CEA mobilehome policy cost? 

The minimum annual premium for CEA standard Homeowners or Homeowners Choice policies is $45. Different factors determine your premium, such as:

Earthquake risk where you live.
Insured value of your mobilehome.
The policy coverages, limits and deductibles you choose.
If your mobile has an earthquake resistant bracing system or foundation system installed.

Find a Mobilehome policy that works with your budget and coverage needs. And use our Premium Calculator to get a policy estimate.







  
What's the difference between Homeowners and Homeowners Choice policies? 

CEA standard Homeowners policies include dwelling, personal property and loss of use coverage bundled together. Choice policies only require dwelling coverage; however, personal property and loss of use can be purchased as separate options, in addition to the dwelling coverage. 

Compare Homeowners Choice and standard Homeowners Policies








  
Is retrofitting required before purchasing a CEA policy?  

It is not required to have the a home retrofitted in order to purchase a CEA policy however, CEA encourages all California homeowners to reduce their risk of earthquake loss. Visit the page Your Earthquake Risk and Preparedness to learn more about preparedness.  
  




Condominium / Condo Unit Owners


  
How much does a CEA condo unit policy cost? 

The minimum annual premium for a CEA Condo Unit Owners policy is $35. Different factors determine your premium, such as:

The earthquake risk where you live.
The market value of the insured condo.
The policy coverages and deductibles you choose.

Find the coverages, limits and deductibles that work with your budget and needs. And use our Premium Calculator to get a policy estimate.







  
Does CEA offer a master earthquake policy for homeowner associations? 

No, but the CEA does offer individual condominium-unit homeowner earthquake insurance. 
  






  
If my HOA doesn't have an earthquake master policy, do I need Loss Assessment coverage? 

Your homeowners association may have insurance for common areas and the exterior and the structure of the building. But the master earthquake policy doesn't cover the inside of your unit or compensate you for loss of use. Your association may also require condo unit owners to share repair costs or pay part of the association's policy deductible through a loss assessment. To learn more about our condo unit policies, download a copy of the condo unit owners brochure. 
  






  
I own my condo unit. Are there coverage options for me? 

Condo unit owners have unique needs. Condo association master earthquake policies usually don't cover damage to your personal belongings or damage to the inside of your home. And while some associations may cover earthquake damage to a condo building's exterior or common areas,  many also require unit owners to pay a portion of the repair costs or the association's policy deductible (by levying a loss assessment). CEA offers a condo unit policy with coverage for your belongings and the interior of your condo unit, as well as loss assessment coverage. 
  






  
What is the highest limit offered for the building property for an individual condo unit owner?  

If selected, the limit on building property for an individual unit owner is $100,000. This will cover items permanently attached such as built in appliances, fixtures, and flooring. For all terms and conditions please read the CEA condominium policy. 
  






  
Is there loss assessment coverage on a CEA condo unit policy? 

Yes. Loss Assessment coverage has options up to $100,000 for an individual unit owner to help cover the cost of special assessments their Home Owners Association (HOA) may assess for the cost of repairing the unit structures, or may be used towards the HOA’s master policy deductible. For all terms and conditions please read the CEA condominium policy.  
  
  




Renters


  
How much does a CEA renters policy c​ost? 

The minimum annual premium for CEA Renters Policy is $35. Different factors determine your premium, such as:

Earthquake risk where you live.
The policy coverages, limits and deductibles you choose.

Find a Renters policy that works with your budget and coverage needs. And use our Premium Calculator to get a policy estimate.







  
I rent, so will my landlord's policy cover my belongings? 

No. If you rent, you need a separate renters policy to cover your personal belongings. CEA renters earthquake insurance insures personal property such as TVs and furniture, with deductibles ranging from 5 to 25 percent, and covers additional living expenses—if you must live and eat elsewhere following a quake—of up to $100,000 with no deductible. 
  




Deductibles and Discounts


  
What are my deductible options? 

Policyholders can choose deductibles of 5%, 10%, 15%, 20% or 25% on all coverages that carry a deductible.
For Homeowners, you have two choices of policies: Homeowners Choice or standard Homeowners . With Homeowners Choice, you have the option of adding Personal Property with a separate deductible--this feature can allow a personal property payment, even if your house isn't substantially damaged.

With Homeowners Choice , you buy dwelling coverage, but may also insure personal property, cover additional living expenses, or both.
Standard Homeowners policy includes dwelling, personal property and additional living expense coverages.
The first $1,500 in Emergency Repairs, as well as the cost to live elsewhere while your residence is being repaired, come with no deductible.








  
Does CEA require policyholders to "pay" a deductible out-of-pocket? 

No. The deductible is the amount deducted from the insured loss—you do not have to pay any portion of your deductible to receive a claim payment. And, two CEA coverages come with zero deductible: the first $1,500 of emergency repairs for homeowners and mobilehome owners, and, if a home can't be occupied after an earthquake, up to $100,000 for Loss of Use expenses. 
  






  
How does CEA's deductible work? 

Policyholders do not have to write a check to the CEA before they get payment on a claim. The deductible is subtracted from the covered damage, and we pay the policyholder the difference. The deductible does not have to be paid up front before we pay a policyholder's claim. Remember, all claim payments are handled through your insurance company's adjuster. 
  






  
Are homeowners eligible for a retrofit discount? 

Yes. In 2016, the CEA began offering a Hazard Reduction Discount, lowering a CEA earthquake insurance premium by up to 20 percent, depending on a variety of factors. You might be eligible to receive a discount if your older house was:

Built before 1979.
Wood-frame construction-type.
Built on a raised foundation.
Frame is bolted to the foundation.
Home has cripple walls, and they are braced with plywood or its equivalent.
Water heater is secured to the building frame.
Homes built on a concrete-slab or combination-type foundation do not qualify.

If a home has...


Cripple walls, they must all be braced with plywood or its equivalent according to California Building Code (CBC) Standards.
Post-and-pier foundation or post-and-beam foundation, the foundation must be modified to CBC Standards.

Note: Homes built on a concrete-slab or combination-type foundation do not qualify.

  
  






  
Are mobilehome owners eligible for a retrofit discount? 

Yes. A CEA policyholder may be eligible for a 23 percent Hazard Reduction Premium Discount, on average, on their mobilehome policy premium if they have one of the following:

Earthquake Resistant Bracing System (ERBS) that will hold a mobilehome in place in its upright position during an earthquake.
Earthquake resistant foundation system: A foundation built on-site that includes supports and piers capable of transferring all weight loads to the ground without failing. Constructed of concrete, metal, treated lumber or wood, or masonry, which are often placed below grade.

In order to qualify for and receive the discount, policyholders who have installed an ERBS or an approved foundation system must provide to their CEA participating insurer a copy of a final inspection report that verifies:

Prior issuance of a building permit, and
That the system and installation meet California Department of Housing and Community Development certification or the local jurisdiction’s building-inspection requirements.








  
What is a cripple wall? 

Generally speaking, a cripple wall is a short wood-framed wall surrounding the crawl space under the house, which needs to be reinforced to help prevent the house from toppling during an earthquake. 
  






  
What is the difference between the 5%, 10%, and 20% Hazard Reduction Discounts? 

A discount is applied for a qualified house based on a number of factors, including the type of verification received, as well as the year the house was constructed:

All qualified houses that are self-verified receive a 5% discount
All qualified houses that are verified by a contractor through the required CEA Earthquake Insurance Dwelling Retrofit form will receive:
	
10% credit if the house was built from 1960 to 1978
20% credit if the house was built before 1960



More information can be found on the Earthquake Retrofit Discounts and Incentives / Hazard Reduction Discounts page 
  






  
On the Hazard Reduction Discount Verification form, does the licensed contractor or structural or civil engineer have to be bonded in order to qualify? 

No, the check box is for information purposes only.  
  




Rates and Premiums


  
Where can I find specimen copies of CEA policies? 


Homeowners Choice Policy Sample - 2016 (PDF)
Standard Homeowners Policy Sample - 2016 (PDF)
Optional Endorsement - Coverage For Breakables (PDF)
Optional Endorsement - Coverage For Exterior Masonry Veneer (PDF)








  
Is earthquake insurance expensive? 

CEA rates are based on a number of factors. While CEA has lowered its statewide average homeowners rates over time by nearly 55 percent, it's important to note that, for example, construction costs in California have increased over 140 percent since 1996. The costs to repair and rebuild after an earthquake will be an expensive burden, but if you don't have earthquake insurance, all the cost to repair any damage will be your cost. Starting in 2016, CEA began offering more coverage and limit choices, more deductible options and more affordable rates—including a 10 percent average statewide rate reduction—to help residents find a policy that best meets their needs and budgets. 
  






  
How does CEA determine the premium amount for its policies? 

CEA premiums are based on science, not profit. Determining factors include the insured value of the home, location, construction year, construction and foundation types, number of stories, and the customer’s coverage choices







  
My premium increased. What can I do to lower the cost of my CEA earthquake coverage? 

There are several ways to lower what you pay for earthquake insurance.

Choose a higher deductible to lower your premium—CEA deductibles range from 5% to 25%, in 5% increments.
If your home is insured under a CEA Homeowners Choice policy, you can reduce your costs by declining personal property or loss of use coverages, or both—you should make that decision carefully, of course, but if you forgo those coverages, you will probably pay less for CEA earthquake insurance.
Make sure your coverage limits make sense for you. Do you rent a 1-bedroom, but have the highest possible personal property limit of $200,000? Make sure your coverage limits accurately reflect what you own.
If you have an older retrofitted house on a raised foundation, you may qualify for a Hazard Reduction Discount of up to 20%, with proper verification. Call your agent or CEA participating insurer for details.








  
Where can I get a premium estimate for a CEA policy? 

Use the Premium Calculator to get a free estimate: 

Select home type (house, mobilehome, condo or rental).
Select location.
Enter current insured value of the house/mobilehome/condo.
Provide basic building construction details if house/mobilehome.
Choose coverages and deductibles.
Get side-by-side estimates of different coverage packages.​

You can then email the estimate to yourself or your agent by clicking "Compare and Send" at the bottom of your screen. 
  




Risk and Safety


  
Why do I need earthquake insurance? 

Most homeowners, mobilehome, condo and renters policies don't cover earthquake damage.
And most Californians live within 30 miles of an active fault, capable of producing damaging earthquakes. There are 2,000 known faults crisscrossing California, and on average, according to the official California Multihazard Mitigation Plan:

Moderate earthquakes (magnitude 5.5) strikes California 3 to 4 times a year.
A strong earthquake (magnitude 6 to 6.9) strikes California every 2 to 3 years.
A major earthquake (magnitude 7 to 7.9) strikes California about every 10 years.

Your earthquake risk is real. According to the Uniform California Earthquake Rupture Forecast (UCERF3), within the next 30 years, there is a:

99.7% chance a 6.7M quake or larger will strike California.
46% chance a 7.5M or greater earthquake will strike, likely in Southern California.
68% chance a 7.0M quake will happen in Northern California.








  
What can I do to prepare for an earthquake? 

Consider creating a disaster preparedness plan. For help, check out our Totally Unprepared Checklist, which is available on our Resources page. It is a great tool to help you prepare for the next damaging earthquake. Remember, as part of your plan, you want to be financially prepared, too. Purchase CEA earthquake insurance to help repair, replace, rebuild, and recover! 
  






  
How do I stay safe during an earthquake? 

That’s a great question. Here are three smart way to stay safe during an earthquake: 

1. Drop, Cover, and Hold On
It’s a classic, and it works. Just keep these simple steps in mind and you’re off to a great start. Use this image as your quick cheat sheet:


2. Learn to Master Earthquake Safety 
We have the ideal video for you to watch and share with your clients. Take 3 minutes to understand the 7 essential steps for earthquake safety.
 




3. Stay Safe Where the Earth Shakes
You can help your clients survive the next damaging earthquake by ordering the Staying Safe Where the Earth Shake booklet from your MVP Agent Store. 
  






  
How can I find out if my home is at risk for earthquake damage? 


Most Californian’s live within 30 miles of an active fault, so chances are, you are located within a potential “damage zone.” Significant earthquakes can damage homes from many miles away.
Many homeowners have a false sense of security because “their home wasn’t damaged in the last major earthquake.” It is highly unlikely that the exact same earthquake will recur. Things like the home’s proximity to the epicenter, depth of the epicenter and soil conditions are all factors that can affect the shaking intensity. 
For more information on how to determine risk, visit these sites: Your Earthquake Risk and Preparedness and http://myhazards.caloes.ca.gov.








  
My house has been retrofitted. Do I still need coverage? 

Yes. Retrofitting your house helps reduce your risk of earthquake damage, but does not eliminate it. Earthquake insurance is designed to help you repair or rebuild your home and replace your personal belongings. It also covers extra living expenses if you must leave your home and temporarily live elsewhere else after an earthquake. Some older, retrofitted houses can receive up to a 20 percent Hazard Reduction Discount on earthquake insurance if properly verified. Call your agent or CEA participating insurer for details. 
  






  
My home isn't on a fault. Why would I need earthquake insurance? 

Most Californians live within 30 miles of an active fault. From even a moderate earthquake, substantial damage may occur miles from the fault or the earthquake epicenter. As recent earthquake history has shown, an earthquake can strike anywhere, at any time, even on previously unknown faults. 
  






  
Will government grants pay to repair earthquake damage to my house? 

Government assistance is not always available. You must first qualify, and grants are often limited to urgent health and safety needs. And government loans for rebuilding may be limited and, like your mortgage, must be repaid. In other words, government assistance is designed to help you get back into your home, not to offer enough funds for you to rebuild or fully replace your damaged or destroyed property. 
  
























